Cell["\<\
In the above graph, we can clearly see both the sinusoidal and exponential \
behavior of the solution. However, since the exponential behavior is so much \
more dominant, we can see the exponential behavior dominate towards the front \
of the graph, and taper off to a complete sinusoid towards the back. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.856201796379323*^9, 3.856201951687653*^9}, {
  3.856202108020935*^9, 3.856202119052662*^9}, {3.856202172272697*^9, 
  3.856202175741713*^9}, {3.856202245704076*^9, 3.856202247337304*^9}, {
  3.856285991957169*^9, 
  3.856285992582837*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"72167b5c-cf5d-4c97-a10f-\
0d407ab68bad"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
3.) Discuss the variation in solutions from the last homework with homogenous \
Dirichlet boundary conditions. How did the change in conditions affect the \
solutions? \
\>", "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8563037736433783`*^9, 3.856303791124502*^9}, {
  3.856303849363636*^9, 3.856303878246173*^9}, {3.856306998471835*^9, 
  3.856306999039867*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"fceb0ba6-32d7-4cdb-aec5-\
fdbe1b08ad34"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In our previous homework, the homogeneous Dirichlet boundary conditions \
lead the heat distribution in our rod to go to zero without variation. While \
this was convenient from a computational standpoint, it severely limits the \
use of such equations in applied settings. Luckily, we are now exploring some \
more complicated cases! In parts a. and b. we still deal with Dirichlet \
boundary conditions, but the left and right sides have been set to one \
respectively. In application, this means the heat distribution will not ever \
go to zero. This makes sense, since the problem is defined such that one side \
is zero and one side is 1 for all values of t greater than zero . \
Interestingly, while looking at the graphs you may note that they are tilted \
in opposite directions along the x-axis. This is consistent with the fact \
that the non-zero values are on opposite ends for these two problems.\n\nThe \
2D heat equation is nice to work with since their is only one constant you \
have to solve for, which is Bm,n unlike in the wave equation where you have \
to solve for Am,n as well as Bm,n. The 2D wave equation also involves the \
sine series.\n\nPart d has us dealing with homogeneous Neumann boundary \
conditions. Since they are defining the rate of temperature change at the \
boundaries as zero, this would be the case where the ends of the rod are \
insulated. This has the neat effect of smoothing the heat distribution over \
time, but at a much slower rate than we have seen in previous problems. In \
this solution we still see the heat going to zero along the length of the \
rod, and given enough time, it would flatten out completely. In this case \
however, this is not due to the boundaries being set to zero , but that the \
integral of the heat distribution along the x-axis at t=0 is equal to zero. \
If we were dealing with an f(x) which were not so symmetrical, we would \
likely find the heat distribution tending toward some other constant.\n\n\
Neumann boundary conditions define the rate of change at the edge of a  \
bounded curve in 2D. These conditions will always result in a cosine series. \
These conditions are often called \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]insulating \
boundaries\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] since they occur at boundaries and \
maintain them. In the heat equation this represents how the temperature is \
changing at boundary.\n\nWith the benefit of hindsight, we can now compare \
our current solutions to the solutions of the previous homework. The results: \
well, they\[CloseCurlyQuote]re a bit disappointing. In both of these two \
homework assignments, we often get identical solutions to certain problems. I \
mean, in both this week and last we got solutions that just ended up being \
planes in space with other solutions resembling a sheet of paper. But, I \
guess I can\[CloseCurlyQuote]t be too upset since the overwhelming amount of \
PDEs in the world are either unsolvable or have no real meaning. Maybe an \
advanced course on the topic would cover other, unique solutions; but I guess \
I should be content with what I have right now. \n\nIn terms of differences, \
the most evident example is the pronounced sinusoidal behavior in this \
homework assignment. Problem \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]d\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \
in-particular exhibits some pretty extreme sinusoidal behavior that\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s a direct result of the large exponential term ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", "2"}], 
    SuperscriptBox["\[Pi]", "2"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "73f23858-65f2-4be2-b8c1-ea9acbdb16b0"],
 ". I also think that the reason ",
 StyleBox["why",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " these problems exhibited more \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]extreme\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] behavior in general is that we\[CloseCurlyQuote]re \
solving  problems with more variables and, as such, more things need to be \
accounted for. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.856306664730258*^9, 3.856306988377781*^9}, {
  3.856307081688113*^9, 3.856307122954994*^9}, {3.856307164211178*^9, 
  3.8563074450651293`*^9}, {3.856307703641858*^9, 3.856307716186895*^9}, {
  3.856307775496421*^9, 3.856307794284658*^9}, {3.8563109655600348`*^9, 
  3.856310967121702*^9}, {3.856311049131311*^9, 
  3.856311049984106*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4eed9745-bf0d-4ccf-8566-\
2be6045d631b"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["3.7 Problems", "Subtitle",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.855972532310232*^9, 
  3.8559725349159107`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"318c0d6c-8c44-421d-b2a7-\
4df43d4ca4ff"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "Plot all solutions to the 2D Wave Equation: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["u", "tt"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox["c", "2"], "(", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["u", "xx"], "+", 
      SubscriptBox["u", "yy"]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "48aeb1b0-43f0-4140-97aa-3de0cb34367b"],
 ". Evaluate the solutions and their behaviors. Discuss characteristics and \
similarities."
}], "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.85597259007798*^9, 3.855972638613401*^9}, {
  3.855972669602578*^9, 
  3.8559726880398808`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2c1d06ef-6cbe-4f21-8b35-\
a1e98bdbf13b"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "a.) u(x,y,0) = Sin[2x]*Sin[y], ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["u", "t"], "(", 
     RowBox[{"x", ",", "y", ",", "0"}], ")"}], "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"fa74b7ee-a635-4c86-b195-a432a7fbfd7e"],
 ", c = 2, a = b = \[Pi]"
}], "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8559726982110357`*^9, 
  3.855972785667902*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e5dc614c-4143-4ab8-b41c-\
f3e5f2e76b94"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For this first 2D solution to the wave equation, I obtained a pretty \
straightforward solution \[LongDash] u(x,y,t) = Sin[2x] * Sin[y] * ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
    RowBox[{"2", 
     SqrtBox["5"], "*", " ", "t"}], "]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->"TraditionalForm",ExpressionUUID->
  "0a69f565-a063-4d07-9bfc-13e34b316f5c"],
 " \[LongDash] given the above criteria. Much like the first problem to 3.6, \
this problem is identical to the in-class counterpart and was not terribly \
difficult to solve.  Now let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s take a look at a physical \
representation of the function. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.856211324099214*^9, 3.856211422773671*^9}, {
  3.856211452985026*^9, 3.856211453449596*^9}, {3.856211498358663*^9, 
  3.8562115855343933`*^9}, {3.8562117890344048`*^9, 
  3.856211795480526*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5d55eb1e-b8b6-4350-9244-\
e560766e8a57"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Corrine", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["u", "5"], "[", 
     RowBox[{"x_", ",", "y_", ",", "t_"}], "]"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
      RowBox[{"2", "x"}], "]"}], "*", 
     RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "y", "]"}], "*", 
     RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
      RowBox[{"2", 
       SqrtBox["5"], "*", "t"}], "]"}]}]}]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Sharuk", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["u", "51"], "[", 
     RowBox[{"x_", ",", "t_"}], "]"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
      RowBox[{"2", "x"}], "]"}], "*", 
     RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
      RowBox[{"2", 
       SqrtBox["5"], "*", "t"}], "]"}]}]}]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Ian", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["u", "52"], "[", 
     RowBox[{"y_", ",", "t_"}], "]"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "y", "]"}], "*", 
     RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
      RowBox[{"2", 
       SqrtBox["5"], "*", "t"}], "]"}]}]}]}], ";"}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8562108023582363`*^9, 3.856210864257154*^9}, {
   3.856211602664257*^9, 3.8562116050561447`*^9}, 3.856211663172048*^9, {
   3.8562861418480797`*^9, 3.8562861986809464`*^9}, {3.856286232440054*^9, 
   3.8562862449612083`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[11]:=",ExpressionUUID->"4c5e974d-56c1-4749-97d4-06fc10b87e53"],

