Cell["\<\
This solution is pretty similar to that of part b. However, these pictures \
have some \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]spikes\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] protruding \
from the pictures with that make them a little harder to view conceptually, \
but are still valid solutions. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.85630838388103*^9, 
  3.856308496565813*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f260ac0c-2740-474b-a7bf-\
41e6f3cabb40"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
3.) What is interesting, or of note about the solutions in 2D?\
\>", "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.856301776381153*^9, 3.856301824023094*^9}, {
  3.856302246041264*^9, 
  3.856302255613866*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8a2e8093-d58a-4633-9a46-\
2f0d0b3f22d9"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Explain how the additional spatial variable affected the solution form.
How would you expect such solutions to appear for the 2D Heat Equation?
Extrapolate and explain what your expectations are for problems that have \
nonhomogeneous boundary conditions.
Then discuss the effects of conditions such as homogeneous Neumann BCs for 2D \
problems. \
\>", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.856301832130127*^9, 
  3.856301947406055*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"014f39ac-99b7-4221-87d1-\
255a7675132d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For these 2d problems, I needed to set my solutions in terms of three \
variables: x, y and t. Aside from making the problems all the more difficult, \
I also needed to deal with only a few solutions  terms at a time. If a way to \
graph these three variable functions exists in Mathematica, I couldn\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t find it. However, I do know that an animation function \
exists in the program, but I could not figure out how to use it given the \
assignment\[CloseCurlyQuote]s time constraints. Problems aside, let\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s dive into the analysis. \n\nGiven the additional spatial \
variable, I decided the best way to graph the 2d problems would be to break \
them up; and so I did. In doing so, I discovered that the solutions tend to \
follow a similar pattern in that the solutions tend to be waves themselves \
and that they all propagate in the same general direction. If I could figure \
out how animate works, I might be able to see this propagation in action, but \
I\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve already said what I want about that. \n\nIf I were to \
find particular 2d solutions to the heat equation, I\[CloseCurlyQuote]d \
expect similar problems and would have to break up any and all solutions that \
I obtained. Problems aside, I also think that solutions would follow a \
similar pattern to what we experienced here in that the solutions to unique \
problems would share a physical resemblance to each other as well as the \
solutions of the individual. \n\nWhen given any 2d P.D. wave equation, I \
would expect any and all solutions to resemble physical waves, go figure. \
Sarcasm aside, this has an intuitive level of sense to it since all waves \
have a peak, trough, wavelength, amplitude and other characteristics that one \
would typically associate with waves. As for the boundary conditions, I think \
the most reasonable expectation to hold would be that our final solution may \
or may not experience damping from any forcing function. This is also \
consistent with what was previously discussed in engineering/ scientific \
applications to P.D.E.s as well as our own personal experience. Natural waves\
\[LongDash]be they ocean waves, waves on a string, etc.\[LongDash]all tend to \
come to a stop since they experience external forces that cause their motion \
to end. However, given modern technology, we can experience what pure, \
unending waves are like and describe their motion. \n\nNonhomogeneous \
boundary conditions require us to find a particular Yp first with those \
nonhomogenous conditions. The solution to this will theoretically solve the \
whole PDE by itself. From here we would find a homogenous Yh with homogenous \
their homogeneous conditions and add it to the Yp.  The addition of Yp + Yh \
will solve the whole, actual, PDE and not the theoretical one that results \
from Yp alone. Nonhomogenous side conditions occur when the conditions exceed \
the range of our current methods to solve PDEs and thus require us to change \
into an equivalent form that are solvable using S.O.V.. then add to original \
solution, again, this is the Yp.\n\nDirichlet: Defined on the function \
boundary itself.\n-With the above definition, we can infer that Dirichlet \
conditions will only ",
 StyleBox["directly",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " impact the boundaries, but the rest of the function will be impacted as a \
result.  \n\nNeumann: Defined on the derivatives. \n-Since Neumann conditions \
directly impact the derivatives, we need to take this into account and also \
realize that we\[CloseCurlyQuote]re working with a rate of change and take \
antiderivatives when appropriate. \n\nRobin: Defined on a linear combination \
of the two. \n-For Robin conditions, we\[CloseCurlyQuote]re going to have to \
take both of the above observations into account, apply dual methods of \
solving the equations, and also account for anything else that may come from \
the problem.\n\nIt\[CloseCurlyQuote]s also worth noting that, since we\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]re solving these PDEs using SOV, our solutions will always \
be a product of however many variables our problem uses. \n\nIn conclusion, \
this homework assignment was a lot of work and produced some interesting \
results. Only time will tell when this will come up again, but for now, I \
think that we have pretty good understanding of the concepts covered in this \
assignment and are looking forward to what comes next. \n"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.85630207654906*^9, 3.8563022326078997`*^9}, {
